    <header>
        <h1>Trading App Workflow</h1>
        <p>MACD Crossover + Retracement Strategy (Professional Breakdown)</p>
    </header>

    <section>
        <h2>Phase 1: Timeframe Selection</h2>
        <p>
            The first step is selecting a timeframe such as <b>1 Hour (1H)</b> or <b>45 Minutes (45M)</b>.
            This timeframe determines how candles are formed and how signals are interpreted.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>All calculations depend on the selected timeframe.</li>
            <li>Once selected, the same timeframe should be used for consistency.</li>
            <li>Shorter timeframe = more signals but more noise.</li>
            <li>Higher timeframe = fewer signals but stronger reliability.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Phase 2: MACD Crossover Detection</h2>
        <p>
            The system identifies the exact point where the <b>MACD line crosses the Signal line</b>.
            This crossover defines the market direction.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Bullish crossover:</b> MACD crosses above Signal → Uptrend</li>
            <li><b>Bearish crossover:</b> MACD crosses below Signal → Downtrend</li>
            <li>The candle at crossover becomes the <b>Reference Candle</b></li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            This reference candle is extremely important because all future calculations are based on it.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Phase 3: Analyze Second Candle</h2>
        <p>
            After identifying the reference candle, the second candle is observed.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Check if price retraces into defined zones (51% - 80%).</li>
            <li>If yes → partial entry (50% capital).</li>
            <li>If deeper retracement (Zone 2) → enter remaining 50%.</li>
            <li>If no retracement → no trade.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Phase 4: Analyze Third Candle</h2>
        <p>
            If the second candle does not confirm entry, the third candle is analyzed.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>If retracement happens → trade can be taken.</li>
            <li>If not → setup is invalid.</li>
            <li>Only second and third candles are considered.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Phase 5: Entry Logic (Pullback Verification)</h2>
        <p>
            The strategy relies on entering during a pullback rather than chasing price.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Zone 1: 51%–80% retracement → First entry</li>
            <li>Zone 2: Deeper retracement → Second entry</li>
            <li>Capital is split to manage risk</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Retracement Calculation Logic</h2>
        <p>
            The reference candle defines the price range:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Range = High - Low</b></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Bullish (Green Candle)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Market direction: Uptrend</li>
            <li>We buy on dips</li>
            <li>Formula: <b>Target Price = High - (Range × Retracement %)</b></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Bearish (Red Candle)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Market direction: Downtrend</li>
            <li>We sell on pullbacks</li>
            <li>Formula: <b>Target Price = Low + (Range × Retracement %)</b></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Important Logic</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Always use IF/ELSE logic based on trend direction</li>
            <li>Do NOT use same formula for both directions</li>
            <li>Wrong formula = invalid trades</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="code">
            if (isUptrend) {
            target = high - (range * retracement);
            } else {
            target = low + (range * retracement);
            }
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Profit & Risk Management</h2>

        <h3>1. Capital Allocation Strategy</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Total capital is divided into <b>two equal parts (50% + 50%)</b>.</li>
            <li>First entry is taken at Zone 1 (initial retracement).</li>
            <li>Second entry is taken only if price reaches deeper retracement (Zone 2).</li>
            <li>This reduces risk of entering too early and improves average entry price.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>2. Stop Loss (SL) Placement</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Stop loss is standardized to <b>30% of the Reference Candle range</b>.</li>
            <li>First compute range: <b>Range = High - Low</b>.</li>
            <li>SL distance = <b>Range × 30%</b>.</li>
            <li><b>Bullish Trade:</b> SL = Entry Price - (Range × 30%).</li>
            <li><b>Bearish Trade:</b> SL = Entry Price + (Range × 30%).</li>
            <li>This creates a consistent, rule-based risk model instead of arbitrary SL placement.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>3. Take Profit (TP) Strategy</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Primary target is typically the <b>High (bullish)</b> or <b>Low (bearish)</b> of the reference candle.
            </li>
            <li>Advanced traders can trail profits beyond this level for extended moves.</li>
            <li>Partial profit booking can be done after price moves in favor.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>4. Risk-Reward Ratio (Detailed Explanation)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Risk</b> = Distance between Entry and Stop Loss.</li>
            <li><b>Reward</b> = Distance between Entry and Target Price.</li>
            <li>Formula: <b>Risk-Reward = Reward ÷ Risk</b></li>
        </ul>

        <p><b>Example (Bullish Trade):</b></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Reference Candle Range = 100 points</li>
            <li>30% SL = 30 points</li>
            <li>Entry at retracement → suppose 60 points below High</li>
            <li>Target = back to High → reward ≈ 60 points</li>
            <li>Risk = 30 points</li>
            <li><b>RR = 60 / 30 = 1:2</b></li>
        </ul>

        <p><b>Interpretation:</b></p>
        <ul>
            <li>1:1 → You gain equal to what you risk (minimum acceptable)</li>
            <li>1:1.5 → Good trade</li>
            <li>1:2 or higher → High-quality setup</li>
        </ul>

        <p><b>Why this matters:</b></p>
        <ul>
            <li>You don’t need high accuracy to be profitable.</li>
            <li>Even with 50% win rate, a 1:2 RR makes you consistently profitable.</li>
            <li>Example: Lose 1 trade (-30), win 1 trade (+60) → Net +30</li>
        </ul>

        <p><b>Key Rule:</b></p>
        <ul>
            <li>If calculated reward is <b>less than 30% SL distance</b>, skip the trade.</li>
            <li>This ensures every trade has a mathematical edge.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>5. Trade Invalidation Rules</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>If price breaks the reference candle range before entry → <b>Cancel trade</b>.</li>
            <li>If no retracement occurs within 2nd and 3rd candles → <b>No trade</b>.</li>
            <li>Avoid forcing trades outside defined rules.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>6. Position Management</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Once first entry is taken, monitor price reaction closely.</li>
            <li>If second entry is triggered, average entry price improves.</li>
            <li>Move SL to breakeven once price reaches halfway to target.</li>
            <li>This protects capital and reduces emotional trading.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>7. Key Principle</h3>
        <p>
            The goal is not to win every trade, but to ensure that <b>wins are larger than losses</b>.
            Consistent application of risk management ensures long-term profitability.
        </p>

